Analysis of Open Source Mental Illness (OSMI) Survey Data¶

Introduction¶

This analysis explores the OSMI survey dataset, covering years from 2014 to 2019 and focusing on mental health in the tech industry. The dataset consists of three tables: Survey, Question, and Answer, cleaned and manipulated for this study.

Main Goals¶

  • Statistical Overview: Generate a snapshot of the dataset through descriptive statistics.
  • Compare Survey Structure: Identify changes in survey questions between 2014 and 2019.
  • Analyze Demographics: Examine the diversity of survey respondents across various factors.
  • Examine Responses: Evaluate answers to critical survey questions, comparing responses between countries.
Text(0, 0.5, 'Respondent Count')

We can see that the structure of the survey has not been consistent over the years. Only a few questions were included in every survey. Most questions asked in 2014 and some in 2016 were not repeated in future surveys. This complicates the analysis because not all answers between different years can be compared and the amount of data which can be analyzed is lower.

However between 2017-2019 all the questions included in surveys were the same.

Majority of the questions which were included every year are demographic. However 5 are directly related to the subject matter.

Most questions in the survey have categorical ordinal (ordered) categorical answers, some are freeform (i.e. any text) and these will be excluded from any further analysis because more advanced NLP techniques would be required for that.

One thing that slightly complicates the matter is that even questions which have ordinal answers do not conform to a single scale (e.g. Likert).

This initial surveys tended to use less questions with boolean, nominal or integer answer. Besides that the types of questions have been mostly consistent.

The increasing median age of respondents might indicate the median age of people working in tech might have been increasing over the years. However, this is just speculation since we can't assume that the sample of people participating in the survey is representative of the population.

The number of non-male respondents has significantly increased starting in 2017. We can't make any meaningful conclusions just based on this either without knowing how representative the survey is.

/Users/paulius/Docs/Projects/Turing/m1s4/venv/lib/python3.9/site-packages/seaborn/axisgrid.py:118: UserWarning: The figure layout has changed to tight
  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)

The overwhelming majority of respondents work in US or Canada. The number of respondents in UK has been high in the initial years but have decreases significantly as the total number of respondents has decreased as well over the last few years.

Looking at the summary of some of the main questions which were included in the survey every year we can see that:

  • Companies where males are overrepresented seem to provide mental health coverage less often.
  • Relatively few companies outside the US and Canada seem to provide metal health coverage (answer might not be comparable due to differences in healthcare systems and insurance models)
  • Americans are more likely to believe that their anonymity is protected when responding to the survey.
  • Workers in US/CAN are likely to have sought treatment but are less likely to discuss this in interviews.

The table shows proportions of respondents across different categories from 2014 to 2019.

Self-Employed: The proportion increased significantly in 2016 (20%) compared to 2014 (11.3%), and then stabilized around 13-14% for subsequent years.

Tech Company: There's a general decline in the proportion of respondents from tech companies, dropping from 81.9% in 2014 to 59% in 2019.

Sought Treatment: Although the proportion decreased from 2014 (81.9%) to 2016 (58.6%), it remained relatively stable around 60% for the following years.

1000 Employees: The proportion of respondents from large companies (>1000 employees) increased over time, starting from 50.5% in 2014 to 31.6% in 2019.

Brought Up Mental Health in Interview: This saw an increase over the years, moving from 19.8% in 2014 to 32.5% in 2019.

Question Analysis¶

The charts below show the relationships some selected answers have with the main demographic variables and their correlations to the other question in the survey (if coefficient is above 0.25).

The answers were selected from all the questions which were available in every survey between 2016 and 2019 based on their subjectively perceived importance and the number of other questions they correlate with.
